long run, is so difficult

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.230
is that the individual
tactics and tools

00:02:24.230 --> 00:02:26.420
and techniques that
people are using

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:28.760
are not only complex
in themselves,

00:02:28.760 --> 00:02:33.950
but importantly, they're
also very interconnected.

00:02:33.950 --> 00:02:39.110
And so it's tempting to obsess
about one or two or three

00:02:39.110 --> 00:02:42.440
individual tactics and
master them, but kind of

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:45.860
lose sight of the big picture.

00:02:45.860 --> 00:02:49.820
And so for example, let's
look at performance marketing.

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:54.680
So there was a recent study
that showed that marketers

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:58.340
are using dozens of
channels and ad formats

00:02:58.340 --> 00:02:59.990
to reach their users.

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:04.340
So this is just looking
at paid marketing.

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:08.240
And for me, that already looks
like a very, very complicated

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:11.720
subject to master-- just
performance marketing.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:13.880
But of course, we haven't
even thought about

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:17.360
or haven't even looked at
all of the organic ways

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:22.400
of driving users to your app,
and the interdependencies

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:24.890
between those.

00:03:24.890 --> 00:03:28.040
Also for us at least, or
when I think about growth,

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:32.190
growth involves much, much
more than user acquisition.

00:03:32.190 --> 00:03:37.190
So in fact, I'm
certain that almost all

00:03:37.190 --> 00:03:39.530
of you here in
the audience today

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:44.490
are working on strategies to
better engage and retain users.

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:48.350
In fact, at the recent Play
event earlier in the year,

00:03:48.350 --> 00:03:50.300
we did roundtable discussions.

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:52.580
And there, developers--
almost every single person

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:56.840
I talked to-- told me that they
obsess about the onboarding

00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:02.060
experience in their app to make
sure that new users sign up

00:04:02.060 --> 00:04:05.120
or activate push
notifications to then later

00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:08.210
be able to target them better
with life cycle marketing

00:04:08.210 --> 00:04:10.370
campaigns.

00:04:10.370 --> 00:04:13.010
Now, those are just
two things-- so

00:04:13.010 --> 00:04:16.160
onboarding experience, or
first-time user experience,

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:17.450
and lifecycle marketing.

00:04:17.450 --> 00:04:19.430
But there are a
lot of other things

00:04:19.430 --> 00:04:22.460
that people are
doing to drive growth

00:04:22.460 --> 00:04:25.040
and engagement and retention
and, ultimately, usage

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:27.080
of their app.

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:30.470
And of course,
eventually, all of us

00:04:30.470 --> 00:04:35.120
will care about revenue
and/or growing revenue.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:37.160
But of course, how much
you focus on revenue

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:40.250
depends on the lifecycle stage
of the venture that you're

00:04:40.250 --> 00:04:43.640
working on or the
maturity of your product.

00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:46.670
So one way that people
are optimizing or growing

00:04:46.670 --> 00:04:50.870
their revenue is by optimizing
their pricing strategy.

00:04:50.870 --> 00:04:54.080
But it's much more than
just deciding on a price.

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:57.050
So developers-- top
developers like Netflix--

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:59.840
they're using a lot of
very subtle strategies.

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:03.740
And they're experimenting
with things like price tiering

00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:08.420
and price anchoring to
influence purchase decisions.

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:10.770
And a lot of you are
doing that as well.

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:13.679
So pricing is only
one of the many things

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:15.470
that people are thinking
about when they're

00:05:15.470 --> 00:05:17.330
thinking about growing revenue.

00:05:17.330 --> 00:05:19.790
You have to think about,
how do you capture value

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:21.740
in the first place
from partners?

00:05:21.740 --> 00:05:24.080
How do you have your
office strategy?

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:26.280
How do you process payments?

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:33.560
So I work with a lot of you,
and a lot of top partners

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:36.710
personally, on a lot of
these topics and issues.

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:42.800
And I think it gets fairly
complex fairly quickly.

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:48.320
And luckily, there are a lot
of people in the growth hacking

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:50.630
community, growth
professionals, that

00:05:50.630 --> 00:05:55.040
are looking for ways to
put some sort of structure

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:00.530
on growth, on this wild
field, on this complex topic,

00:06:00.530 --> 00:06:03.320
and trying to understand
all of the interdependencies

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:08.030
and enable them to
prioritize better

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:11.500
and to ultimately accelerate
their growth strategy.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:15.530
So one of these people will
be on stage later-- Andy.

00:06:15.530 --> 00:06:18.170
And a couple of people around
him in the growth hacking

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:21.800
community have been thinking
a lot about one of these tools

00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:23.570
to structure growth.

00:06:23.570 --> 00:06:28.130
And I want to give you a very
brief introduction to a growth

00:06:28.130 --> 00:06:29.040
hacking framework.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:33.080
So the first thing
that you should do

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:36.080
is actually to take a step back.

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:40.520
And so just before looking
at any of the tools, tactics,

00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:44.180
and techniques, think about your
high-level business objectives,

00:06:44.180 --> 00:06:45.060
whatever they are.

00:06:45.060 --> 00:06:47.600
So if you're early
in your venture,

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:49.870
maybe you're just
trying to validate

00:06:49.870 --> 00:06:52.310
a minimum viable product.

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:55.310
Or you're trying to
double sales on mobile.

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:57.870
Or you're maybe
looking for investment,

00:06:57.870 --> 00:07:00.650
and you want to raise
a round of investments.

00:07:00.650 --> 00:07:05.360
Now think about how
those high-level business

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:11.400
objectives-- what do they
mean for your growth strategy,

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:14.750
for how you define
growth for yourself?

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:19.070
And you will start to
notice that you'll probably,

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:22.020
without looking at
anything individual,

00:07:22.020 --> 00:07:24.500
be interested to
focus more strongly

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:26.660
on one of these three things.

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:28.770
Maybe you'll focus on all.

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:33.050
But it will sort of give
you an initial idea on where

00:07:33.050 --> 00:07:37.020
you might want to focus.

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:38.720
Also, of course,
important are not

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.240
just your business objectives
but also your resources

00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:43.020
and your constraints.

00:07:43.020 --> 00:07:46.320
And I'll talk about that
a little bit later on.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:50.930
So let's talk about
how to apply that.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:57.070
So tactics-- all the
things I mentioned earlier

00:07:57.070 --> 00:08:00.390
are your kind of tools,
tactics, strategies that

00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:03.520
are available for you to use.

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:06.780
And this, by the way, is
not an exhaustive list.

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:09.290
There are many, many other
things that people are doing.

00:08:09.290 --> 00:08:12.630
But when you're
evaluating an activity,

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:15.390
think about, how does
this particular activity

00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:17.660
fit into my overall strategy?

00:08:17.660 --> 00:08:23.990
So you can do that for the
activities that foster user

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:26.600
acquisition or accelerate
user acquisition.

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:29.900
You can do that for
activities that increase

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:32.010
engagement and retention.

00:08:32.010 --> 00:08:35.240
And you can do that
for growing revenue.

00:08:35.240 --> 00:08:38.370
And I'm not saying you should
be doing all of these things.

00:08:38.370 --> 00:08:41.159
You should be looking at
every single tactic in light

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:44.900
of your overall objectives,
your resources, and maybe

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:46.280
your constraints.

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:49.910
But then once you have sort
of assembled your toolset

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:52.550
for growth, there's
another important thing

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:54.050
that you need to do.

00:08:54.050 --> 00:08:58.380
And that is build the right
business intelligence tools

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:01.580
and infrastructure to be
able to track your progress.

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:04.350
And I can't emphasize
how important this is.

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:06.840
Because when you
invest in these areas,

00:09:06.840 --> 00:09:09.900
you're using resources that
you might use for other things

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:10.920
instead.

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:14.540
So you need to be able to
track the impact that you're

00:09:14.540 --> 00:09:17.930
having, that your teams are
having, on these individual

00:09:17.930 --> 00:09:18.470
areas.

00:09:18.470 --> 00:09:20.690
So you might want
to assign one or two

00:09:20.690 --> 00:09:24.320
actionable and measurable KPIs
to each of those investments.

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:26.990
So maybe when you're thinking
about optimizing your Play

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:30.600
listing, think about the visit
to in-store conversion rate

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:32.300
and how all the things
that you're doing

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:34.460
are impacting that
in the long run.

00:09:34.460 --> 00:09:36.870
Or when you're thinking
of your onboarding flow,

00:09:36.870 --> 00:09:41.610
define a metric that captures
your activation rate-- how

00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:45.725
good you are at activating
users, how good you are

00:09:45.725 --> 00:09:47.960
at introducing the
product to your users

00:09:47.960 --> 00:09:49.860
when they install the app.

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:52.400
Or when you're thinking
about growing revenue,

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:56.460
you might think, OK, here
are my payment processors.

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:58.310
What's the percentage
of failed payments?

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:00.900
And how can I
increase the coverage

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:02.930
when I enter new markets?

00:10:02.930 --> 00:10:04.860
So that's very
important-- the KPIs

00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:09.400
and being able to measure them.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:12.270
Now let's think
of one-- I'd like

00:10:12.270 --> 00:10:15.640
to explain a very simple
application of this framework.

00:10:15.640 --> 00:10:18.780
It's not an exercise
in pretty drawings.

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:22.320
But think of the concept
of a growth card, right?

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:27.110
So you've selected the
activities you want to do.

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:28.590
You've got your KPIs.

00:10:28.590 --> 00:10:29.970
And you can measure them.

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:33.700
Now try to benchmark against
either internal goals

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:35.220
or industry averages.

00:10:35.220 --> 00:10:37.800
So you might actually find--
let's go back to the Play Store

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:39.040
optimization example.

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:42.250
You might actually find
that your conversion rate

00:10:42.250 --> 00:10:46.470
is actually very good
compared to country benchmarks

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:48.210
or industry benchmarks.

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:52.270
You might find that maybe
your activation rate is OK.

00:10:52.270 --> 00:10:53.840
It's not super great.

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:56.620
But compared to the goals
you set for yourself,

00:10:56.620 --> 00:10:58.390
it's quite good.

00:10:58.390 --> 00:11:02.660
But then you might find that
payment is really an issue.

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:05.670
And I'm just using
these as examples.

00:11:05.670 --> 00:11:09.940
But this is how having a
scorecard to guide your growth

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:16.100
strategy can be very, very,
very useful and helpful.

00:11:16.100 --> 00:11:21.810
So that's enough theory for
one afternoon after lunch.

00:11:21.810 --> 00:11:24.570
Now I would like to talk
a little bit about what

00:11:24.570 --> 00:11:28.470
our top Android
developers are doing

00:11:28.470 --> 00:11:32.770
with some of these
techniques to drive growth.

00:11:32.770 --> 00:11:36.330
Now, I'll be focusing mostly
on the organic techniques.

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:38.700
That's what I do in my day job.

00:11:38.700 --> 00:11:40.810
And then Marie will come
up and talk a little bit

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:42.430
about paid techniques.

00:11:42.430 --> 00:11:48.100
So first up, I'd like to
talk a little bit about Clue.

00:11:48.100 --> 00:11:51.400
So this is a period tracking
and female health app.

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:53.890
And they're based
here in Berlin.

00:11:53.890 --> 00:12:01.270
So late last year, they
went through an exercise

00:12:01.270 --> 00:12:05.420
quite similar to
the growth framework

00:12:05.420 --> 00:12:07.170
that I introduced just before.

00:12:07.170 --> 00:12:11.500
So we were trying to figure
out, where are the bottlenecks,

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:14.950
or which areas needed more
investment to accelerate

00:12:14.950 --> 00:12:16.630
the growth curve on Android?

00:12:16.630 --> 00:12:18.370
And one of the things
that we identified

00:12:18.370 --> 00:12:23.110
was that the in-store
conversion rate was quite low,

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:25.600
or was lower than
it needed to be.

00:12:25.600 --> 00:12:28.630
So the folks at
Clue really came up

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:32.080
with a long-term strategy of
running lots of little Play

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:35.910
listing experiments to
increase the conversion rate.

00:12:35.910 --> 00:12:38.730
And over the course
of about six months,

00:12:38.730 --> 00:12:42.250
they increased the
conversion rate by 24%.

00:12:42.250 --> 00:12:43.320
And that's huge.

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:47.770
So that means that 24%
more users install the app

00:12:47.770 --> 00:12:51.760
without spending anything
more on advertising or doing

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:53.230
any PR work or anything.

00:12:53.230 --> 00:12:55.180
So that's just with the
users that are already

00:12:55.180 --> 00:12:57.100
arriving on the Play listing.

00:12:57.100 --> 00:13:00.850
So just to give
you one quick test,

00:13:00.850 --> 00:13:04.950
so which of the two
images do you think

00:13:04.950 --> 00:13:10.992
had a higher visit to download
conversion rate, the left one

00:13:10.992 --> 00:13:11.700
or the right one?

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:15.904
So have a show of hands for
the left one, on your left.

00:13:15.904 --> 00:13:17.070
OK, so that's the black one.

00:13:17.070 --> 00:13:19.510
OK, and the others?

00:13:19.510 --> 00:13:21.210
OK, yeah, so the
white one-- there's

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:25.120
actually two factors there
that got tested individually.

00:13:25.120 --> 00:13:29.970
The white phone drove a
higher conversion rate

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:31.600
and larger image.

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:34.645
So that's a really,
really cool insight here.

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:39.580
The next thing I
want to talk about,

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:42.450
in terms of the toolsets
that you have available,

00:13:42.450 --> 00:13:46.150
is an example from a non-profit,
which is ShareTheMeal,

00:13:46.150 --> 00:13:48.420
also based here in Berlin.

00:13:48.420 --> 00:13:53.280
And these guys, I'm sure, also
did a very sophisticated growth

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:53.910
analysis.

00:13:53.910 --> 00:13:56.290
But one of the
restrictions that they have

00:13:56.290 --> 00:13:57.880
is that they're a non-profit.

00:13:57.880 --> 00:14:01.510
So they can't actually spend
any money on advertising.

00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:05.190
So they sort of evaluated
their constraints

00:14:05.190 --> 00:14:07.560
and then thought, well, one
of the things we can do,

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:09.780
and we can do very well,
is public relations.

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:13.410
And I think it's a tool
that's often overlooked,

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:15.060
because it's hard to do well.

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:18.710
But when you do it well, it
can be very, very powerful.

00:14:18.710 --> 00:14:21.420
So it's also hard to track.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:23.530
But they have to
track the impact.

00:14:23.530 --> 00:14:28.110
So they estimate about
50% of all total installs

00:14:28.110 --> 00:14:30.210
were driven by public relations.

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:33.670
And a couple of the
insights there are you

00:14:33.670 --> 00:14:36.480
need to really focus on
excellent messaging and having

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:40.680
the right hooks, and also
to combine public relations

00:14:40.680 --> 00:14:47.080
with other initiatives, such
as partnerships work, or maybe

00:14:47.080 --> 00:14:50.860
press work partnerships, and
maybe viral hooks, something

00:14:50.860 --> 00:14:52.816
like that.

00:14:52.816 --> 00:14:55.970
I also want to talk a
little bit about virality.

00:14:55.970 --> 00:15:00.171
So I'm sure you guys
all know Dubsmash.

00:15:00.171 --> 00:15:01.670
I don't know if
anyone from Dubsmash

00:15:01.670 --> 00:15:04.460
is here today-- I think so.

00:15:04.460 --> 00:15:08.790
No-- or maybe you
don't want to say.

00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:13.390
So Dubsmash is a social
video messaging platform.

00:15:13.390 --> 00:15:17.020
And basically what it does is
it allows you to create videos

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:18.860
for yourself that are dubbed.

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:20.930
And you can lip sync to songs.

00:15:20.930 --> 00:15:22.940
And this is really, really fun.

00:15:22.940 --> 00:15:27.690
And in a way, virality is
built into the product, right?

00:15:27.690 --> 00:15:30.920
It's not very fun looking
at yourself singing along

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:31.790
to songs.

00:15:31.790 --> 00:15:36.320
So sharing and reaching
other users is built in.

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:38.030
And it has been
hugely successful.

00:15:38.030 --> 00:15:40.200
And growth has been phenomenal.

00:15:40.200 --> 00:15:44.960
But the point I want to make
is that even if virality

00:15:44.960 --> 00:15:47.890
isn't built into your product--
so if your product isn't

00:15:47.890 --> 00:15:50.930
the perfect fit for
viral mechanics--

00:15:50.930 --> 00:15:53.450
there are a couple of
things that you can look out

00:15:53.450 --> 00:15:58.700
for to make sure that you make
sharing as easy as possible.

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:00.760
So there are really two factors.

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:02.940
One has a very fun name.

00:16:02.940 --> 00:16:04.610
It's called the K factor.

00:16:04.610 --> 00:16:09.830
And it basically describes,
how many new users does

00:16:09.830 --> 00:16:11.600
one user bring into the app?

00:16:11.600 --> 00:16:13.340
So that's something
that you might

00:16:13.340 --> 00:16:17.940
want to work on improving
by making it easier

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:20.370
to share with other users.

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:25.310
So that can have a really nice
impact on your organic growth.

00:16:25.310 --> 00:16:27.530
Another factor that you
might want to look at

00:16:27.530 --> 00:16:29.300
is the cycle time.

00:16:29.300 --> 00:16:32.880
And that just means,
how short or how long is

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:36.440
the interval between me sharing
with friends and those friends

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:38.510
coming back to the
app or installing

00:16:38.510 --> 00:16:40.940
the app for the first time
and then sharing again?

00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:45.590
So shortening that time can also
be a very, very, very powerful

00:16:45.590 --> 00:16:48.620
factor of increasing the
viral growth of your app.

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:53.000
So think about making sharing
easy, accessible, encouraging,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.260
incentivizing sharing.

00:16:57.220 --> 00:17:01.390
One final thing I want to talk
about in this quick session

00:17:01.390 --> 00:17:03.790
is cross-promotion.

00:17:03.790 --> 00:17:08.950
So cross-promotion, if you
already have a popular app,

00:17:08.950 --> 00:17:10.740
can be a very,
very powerful tool.

00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:15.420
So Freeletics did
this very well.

00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:21.220
So for me, cross-promotion isn't
just injecting an interstitial

00:17:21.220 --> 00:17:23.050
and showing it to all
your existing users

00:17:23.050 --> 00:17:24.650
to promote a new product.

00:17:24.650 --> 00:17:27.349
But doing it in a clever
way works very well.

00:17:27.349 --> 00:17:30.970
So for example, Freeletics
injected nutrition information

00:17:30.970 --> 00:17:35.050
