00:34:13.340 --> 00:34:15.885
focused on user
retention, which I'm

00:34:15.885 --> 00:34:18.010
going to talk about a little
bit today and tell you

00:34:18.010 --> 00:34:21.510
why I think it's the most
important growth metric.

00:34:21.510 --> 00:34:24.110
And I'll just give you
a little bit of insight

00:34:24.110 --> 00:34:28.170
into some of the things that we
did at SoundCloud to increase

00:34:28.170 --> 00:34:31.070
retention.

00:34:31.070 --> 00:34:36.230
So retention-- it's
really scary when you look

00:34:36.230 --> 00:34:37.710
at this graph on the right.

00:34:37.710 --> 00:34:40.130
This is a graph that
I often refer to.

00:34:40.130 --> 00:34:45.150
It was published by Andrew
Chen in one of his blog posts.

00:34:45.150 --> 00:34:48.860
And it shows the average
retention of Android apps

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:50.380
in the Play Store.

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:52.710
And it shows the blue
line there at the top.

00:34:52.710 --> 00:34:55.520
That's apps in the top 10.

00:34:55.520 --> 00:35:00.090
And what you see on
this curve is that even

00:35:00.090 --> 00:35:05.030
a top 10 app loses 50% of its
users in the first 90 days.

00:35:05.030 --> 00:35:07.410
And if the app is
not in the top 10,

00:35:07.410 --> 00:35:10.630
it's likely to be retaining
users significantly poorer

00:35:10.630 --> 00:35:11.130
than that.

00:35:11.130 --> 00:35:13.860
It's a really tough
game to retain users.

00:35:13.860 --> 00:35:19.860
Because the switching cost for
a user to switch to another app

00:35:19.860 --> 00:35:22.590
or just to discard your
app is basically zero.

00:35:22.590 --> 00:35:26.480
So it's a constant challenge
to keep your users engaged

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:28.172
and retained.

00:35:28.172 --> 00:35:30.380
And of course, if you're
spending money on marketing,

00:35:30.380 --> 00:35:33.227
it's really scary to
think that actually you're

00:35:33.227 --> 00:35:35.310
paying to acquire users
who are probably not going

00:35:35.310 --> 00:35:36.960
to stick around.

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:39.300
So anything you can do
to improve retention

00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:41.260
gives you compound growth
over the long term.

00:35:41.260 --> 00:35:44.490
And it's going to also be a
multiplier on your acquisition

00:35:44.490 --> 00:35:47.230
efforts.

00:35:47.230 --> 00:35:50.500
So at SoundCloud, the way
that we looked at retention

00:35:50.500 --> 00:35:54.070
was-- I mean, you can
think about retention

00:35:54.070 --> 00:35:59.900
in terms of when you look at
your users in any given period.

00:35:59.900 --> 00:36:01.540
So for example,
here's an example

00:36:01.540 --> 00:36:04.940
from the May users
at SoundCloud.

00:36:04.940 --> 00:36:07.040
They broke into these
three different buckets.

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:08.590
So you can think
about you always

00:36:08.590 --> 00:36:11.560
have some new users
who just arrived.

00:36:11.560 --> 00:36:14.500
And then at SoundCloud
we talked about repeat

00:36:14.500 --> 00:36:15.494
and returning users.

00:36:15.494 --> 00:36:16.910
So I'm going to
just take a moment

00:36:16.910 --> 00:36:19.790
to explain the difference
between those two buckets.

00:36:19.790 --> 00:36:23.860
So a repeat user is somebody
who was here in the last period.

00:36:23.860 --> 00:36:26.230
And he's here again this
period, or she is here again

00:36:26.230 --> 00:36:27.410
this period.

00:36:27.410 --> 00:36:31.780
So this is a loyal user
who is currently engaged

00:36:31.780 --> 00:36:34.884
and is using your app regularly.

00:36:34.884 --> 00:36:36.550
What you often find
is that there's also

00:36:36.550 --> 00:36:40.750
a large bucket of what we
refer to as returning users.

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:45.736
So these are users who were
not seen in the last period.

00:36:45.736 --> 00:36:47.110
So they were not
seen last month.

00:36:47.110 --> 00:36:48.550
But they're here this month.

00:36:48.550 --> 00:36:51.279
But they signed up more
than one month ago.

00:36:51.279 --> 00:36:53.320
And this bucket actually
is usually pretty large,

00:36:53.320 --> 00:36:55.690
particularly if your app's
been around for a while.

00:36:55.690 --> 00:36:57.500
And these users
haven't necessarily

00:36:57.500 --> 00:37:00.850
churned, in the sense
that they've really

00:37:00.850 --> 00:37:01.690
abandoned your app.

00:37:01.690 --> 00:37:04.190
They might just be
very casual users.

00:37:04.190 --> 00:37:08.020
Maybe they use your app
once or twice a month,

00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:10.600
or a few times a year.

00:37:10.600 --> 00:37:14.030
And depending on your app and
the particular kind of use case

00:37:14.030 --> 00:37:15.610
that you're solving,
maybe that's OK.

00:37:15.610 --> 00:37:17.350
But probably most
apps, you really

00:37:17.350 --> 00:37:20.080
want users coming back every
week or even every day,

00:37:20.080 --> 00:37:21.880
or even multiple times per day.

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:24.920
So really the way that we
approached it at SoundCloud

00:37:24.920 --> 00:37:26.560
was that we wanted
people listening

00:37:26.560 --> 00:37:30.250
to music on SoundCloud every
day, preferably for many hours.

00:37:30.250 --> 00:37:32.590
And so really it was all
about growing that repeat user

00:37:32.590 --> 00:37:35.620
bucket-- turning new
users into repeat users

00:37:35.620 --> 00:37:39.620
and then keeping them
there, and then reactivating

00:37:39.620 --> 00:37:41.500
users who had lapsed.

00:37:41.500 --> 00:37:43.270
But reactivation
is really tough.

00:37:43.270 --> 00:37:46.310
And I'll talk a bit
more about that later.

00:37:46.310 --> 00:37:52.960
So how do we approach this
idea of keeping users engaged,

00:37:52.960 --> 00:37:56.070
keeping users from
dropping out of this loop?

00:37:56.070 --> 00:38:00.550
And the way that I sort
of conceptualize it

00:38:00.550 --> 00:38:02.380
is that you're building
growth machines.

00:38:02.380 --> 00:38:05.870
You want to build
repeatable loops, processes,

00:38:05.870 --> 00:38:08.830
which through
testing you've proven

00:38:08.830 --> 00:38:12.670
to have a strong impact--
or a positive impact

00:38:12.670 --> 00:38:15.170
at least-- on your
retention numbers.

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:19.210
So this could be-- I'll talk
about activity notifications

00:38:19.210 --> 00:38:21.010
as a prime example
of this in a minute.

00:38:21.010 --> 00:38:23.590
But there are other
things you can do.

00:38:23.590 --> 00:38:27.760
It could be a loyalty scheme
with points or gamification,

00:38:27.760 --> 00:38:29.260
something like
this, anything you

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:34.000
can do that basically you can
put it on sort of autopilot.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.380
Once you've tested it and
optimized it and iterated

00:38:36.380 --> 00:38:38.650
on it to a certain level,
it just keeps going.

00:38:38.650 --> 00:38:42.230
And it keeps pushing some users
into a higher engaged state.

00:38:42.230 --> 00:38:44.260
And it's basically
interacting with users

00:38:44.260 --> 00:38:45.613
ideally before they churn.

00:38:48.790 --> 00:38:52.390
And so I'll talk a little bit
about activity notifications,

00:38:52.390 --> 00:38:55.160
which was actually
one of the projects

00:38:55.160 --> 00:38:56.920
that I spent most
of the last year

00:38:56.920 --> 00:38:58.420
really building
up at SoundCloud.

00:38:58.420 --> 00:39:02.380
It was to build up a new
activity notification

00:39:02.380 --> 00:39:05.350
infrastructure for the company.

00:39:05.350 --> 00:39:06.820
So what are activity
notifications?

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:09.650
They're real-time
notifications--

00:39:09.650 --> 00:39:12.559
could be push, which was
actually the first channel

00:39:12.559 --> 00:39:13.600
that we deployed them to.

00:39:13.600 --> 00:39:15.350
But it can also be over email.

00:39:15.350 --> 00:39:16.416
Could be SMS.

00:39:16.416 --> 00:39:18.040
The channel is less
important, I guess,

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:21.020
than the concept,
which is that you're

00:39:21.020 --> 00:39:23.440
getting in touch with the
user to tell them something

00:39:23.440 --> 00:39:26.080
hopefully interesting
and relevant to them

00:39:26.080 --> 00:39:29.332
in a timely fashion about
something that's happened when

00:39:29.332 --> 00:39:30.290
they're not in the app.

00:39:30.290 --> 00:39:31.750
Now, this is not
always applicable

00:39:31.750 --> 00:39:33.020
to every app scenario.

00:39:33.020 --> 00:39:34.762
But at SoundCloud,
for example, there

00:39:34.762 --> 00:39:37.220
are plenty of things that happen
when you're not in the app

00:39:37.220 --> 00:39:38.290
that you might be interested in.

00:39:38.290 --> 00:39:40.250
It could be that artists
that you're following

00:39:40.250 --> 00:39:41.590
have released new tracks.

00:39:41.590 --> 00:39:43.520
And you might want to
be told about them.

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:44.920
Because you might want to
come and listen to them.

00:39:44.920 --> 00:39:47.050
It could be that I've
created a playlist,

00:39:47.050 --> 00:39:49.270
and somebody has
interacted with it.

00:39:49.270 --> 00:39:52.090
Somebody has liked it or
reposted it somewhere.

00:39:52.090 --> 00:39:56.440
And so these kind of social
interactions, social signals--

00:39:56.440 --> 00:39:57.665
or just new content.

00:39:57.665 --> 00:39:58.790
New content is a great one.

00:39:58.790 --> 00:40:00.920
And it definitely was
the highest performer

00:40:00.920 --> 00:40:04.459
for SoundCloud in terms of
being able to tell people

00:40:04.459 --> 00:40:06.250
that, hey, there's new
music that you might

00:40:06.250 --> 00:40:07.786
want to come and listen to.

00:40:07.786 --> 00:40:11.130
That was fantastic in
terms of performance.

00:40:11.130 --> 00:40:14.650
So just to give you some idea,
with the new notifications

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:18.770
that we rolled out, we built
out five new notification types.

00:40:18.770 --> 00:40:21.940
And between that
combination, we were

00:40:21.940 --> 00:40:25.360
able to increase
retention by around 5%--

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:32.240
absolute percentage points,
which is pretty significant.

00:40:32.240 --> 00:40:35.380
So what did we actually build?

00:40:35.380 --> 00:40:39.900
It's more than just
coding these notifications

00:40:39.900 --> 00:40:42.190
to say, OK, tell the user
that something happened.

00:40:42.190 --> 00:40:45.000
What we actually
wanted to build was

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:48.150
a measurement and experimental
framework around that such

00:40:48.150 --> 00:40:51.537
that we're actually
able to test and iterate

00:40:51.537 --> 00:40:53.620
on these notifications,
and to measure the impact.

00:40:53.620 --> 00:40:56.070
Measurement is really a
tough thing with retention.

00:40:56.070 --> 00:40:59.690
Because everything
affects retention.

00:40:59.690 --> 00:41:01.150
Any product change
that you make is

00:41:01.150 --> 00:41:02.730
likely to affect your retention.

00:41:02.730 --> 00:41:05.270
Your acquisition mix will
also affect your attention.

00:41:05.270 --> 00:41:10.450
So it's really important when
you're running any initiative

00:41:10.450 --> 00:41:13.480
that you hope to improve
retention that you always

00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:14.980
have some kind of
control group that

00:41:14.980 --> 00:41:17.047
is not exposed to
whatever change

00:41:17.047 --> 00:41:18.130
that you're going to make.

00:41:18.130 --> 00:41:20.232
And that control
group is basically

00:41:20.232 --> 00:41:21.690
representing
everything else that's

00:41:21.690 --> 00:41:22.731
going on in the platform.

00:41:22.731 --> 00:41:25.650
Because it's quite a
volatile number typically.

00:41:25.650 --> 00:41:27.670
So we always had a
group of users who never

00:41:27.670 --> 00:41:30.300
received any notifications.

00:41:30.300 --> 00:41:34.110
And then we would test our new
notifications with test groups

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:38.290
and A/B test all the while
with copy, with timing,

00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:42.400
with the different kind
of mix and combination

00:41:42.400 --> 00:41:44.770
of notifications
that we would send.

00:41:44.770 --> 00:41:46.940
So there's a lot of
experiments to run.

00:41:46.940 --> 00:41:49.569
And just as Max was
saying, it's something

00:41:49.569 --> 00:41:50.610
that's never really done.

00:41:50.610 --> 00:41:53.460
It's never really finished.

00:41:53.460 --> 00:41:56.710
So yeah, SoundCloud
will continue

00:41:56.710 --> 00:41:58.420
to iterate on these
notifications,

00:41:58.420 --> 00:41:59.400
to build out new types.

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:02.560
And I think the next
phase, now that we

00:42:02.560 --> 00:42:06.550
have a pretty cool
notification system,

00:42:06.550 --> 00:42:09.160
is that they'll start to
add a layer of intelligence

00:42:09.160 --> 00:42:11.230
on top of that,
so getting smarter

00:42:11.230 --> 00:42:14.740
about optimizing for
relevance of notifications,

00:42:14.740 --> 00:42:17.800
which is super important.

00:42:17.800 --> 00:42:20.650
And so sort of final
points just on how

00:42:20.650 --> 00:42:22.840
to build good
notifications-- it's

00:42:22.840 --> 00:42:25.144
really all about
personalization.

00:42:25.144 --> 00:42:26.560
And again, this
kind of comes back

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:29.400
to the point about iteration.

00:42:29.400 --> 00:42:33.750
So we have a
reactivation notification

00:42:33.750 --> 00:42:36.610
that we send to users
when we haven't seen them

00:42:36.610 --> 00:42:39.940
in the app for five
days at SoundCloud.

00:42:39.940 --> 00:42:43.000
Because we figured out--
again, through testing--

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.610
that five days was a good
time to interact with the user

00:42:45.610 --> 00:42:48.250
before they're really
likely to churn completely.

00:42:48.250 --> 00:42:52.420
But they're already sort of at
risk of churn at that point.

00:42:52.420 --> 00:42:53.900
So we'd send them
a notification.

00:42:53.900 --> 00:42:56.130
And probably like
a lot of people

00:42:56.130 --> 00:42:58.469
who start off with
re-activation,

00:42:58.469 --> 00:43:00.010
we started with
something very basic.

00:43:00.010 --> 00:43:04.300
It was like, hey, come back and
find more music on SoundCloud--

00:43:04.300 --> 00:43:08.730
basically just a very generic,
we miss you, kind of message.

00:43:08.730 --> 00:43:12.690
Yeah, perhaps unsurprisingly,
the click rate was super poor.

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:14.920
The impact was
still worth having.

00:43:14.920 --> 00:43:17.507
But it was pretty minimal.

00:43:17.507 --> 00:43:19.590
And so we thought, OK, how
can we iterate on that?

00:43:19.590 --> 00:43:23.670
So what we ended up with,
which is performing way better,

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:26.560
was kind of a three-tiered
approach, where we look at, OK,

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:30.790
has this user shown some kind
of engagement within the app

00:43:30.790 --> 00:43:33.750
that we can use in our
re-activation message?

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:36.879
So we looked at, has
a user liked a track?

00:43:36.879 --> 00:43:38.920
Because that's a really
high level of engagement,

00:43:38.920 --> 00:43:41.880
if they've actually
hit the Like button.

00:43:41.880 --> 00:43:44.550
And so if a user liked
a track in the past,

00:43:44.550 --> 00:43:46.320
we look at the last
track that they liked.

00:43:46.320 --> 00:43:48.340
And in that
re-activation message,

00:43:48.340 --> 00:43:52.497
we say, hey-- not just come
back and find some more music

00:43:52.497 --> 00:43:53.080
on SoundCloud.

00:43:53.080 --> 00:43:55.205
But we say, hey, come back
and find some more music

00:43:55.205 --> 00:43:59.170
from Artist X-- Artist X
being the creator of the track

00:43:59.170 --> 00:44:00.840
that they liked.

00:44:00.840 --> 00:44:02.691
And if they haven't
liked a track,

00:44:02.691 --> 00:44:04.690
then we look at the last
track that they played.

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:05.880
And we use that as a signal.

00:44:05.880 --> 00:44:07.463
And we personalize
it in the same way.

00:44:07.463 --> 00:44:10.000
So if I listened to a Britney
Spears track as my last track,

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:12.041
then we'd say, hey, come
back and find more music

00:44:12.041 --> 00:44:13.360
from Britney Spears.

00:44:13.360 --> 00:44:17.380
And we found that by using what
you know about the user's usage

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:21.880
history in those messages, you
can really increase the click

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:23.110
rate dramatically.

00:44:23.110 --> 00:44:26.050
I think it was something like a
5x increase in our click rate,

00:44:26.050 --> 00:44:29.800
albeit from a very low base.

00:44:29.800 --> 00:44:32.222
Yeah, time of day can
also be pretty important.

00:44:32.222 --> 00:44:34.990
It's probably a good idea not
to be sending push notifications

00:44:34.990 --> 00:44:38.087
to people in the
middle of the night.

00:44:38.087 --> 00:44:39.920
Of course, if it's a
real-time notification,

00:44:39.920 --> 00:44:41.770
if it's important
enough, maybe some people

00:44:41.770 --> 00:44:43.650
want to be woken up.

00:44:43.650 --> 00:44:47.750
But yeah, again, it's
something to test.

00:44:47.750 --> 00:44:49.640
And yeah, really
importantly-- also

00:44:49.640 --> 00:44:52.380
to give users granular
control over notifications.

00:44:52.380 --> 00:44:56.860
If they can just opt in or out
of notifications in general,

00:44:56.860 --> 00:45:00.729
that's going to really
limit your boldness

00:45:00.729 --> 00:45:02.020
when you're testing new things.

00:45:02.020 --> 00:45:04.306
Because you'll be worried
about people opting out

00:45:04.306 --> 00:45:05.680
of push notifications
altogether,

00:45:05.680 --> 00:45:08.340
which is a valid concern.

00:45:08.340 --> 00:45:10.270
If you give users
the option to opt out

00:45:10.270 --> 00:45:13.010
of every individual
class of notifications--

00:45:13.010 --> 00:45:16.110
so in other words, say I want
to be told about new tracks.

00:45:16.110 --> 00:45:17.980
But I don't care if
people are following me.

00:45:17.980 --> 00:45:20.500
I don't want to be
notified about that.

00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:22.920
By giving people that
granular level of control,

00:45:22.920 --> 00:45:26.230
you can be more experimental
and try bigger ideas.

00:45:26.230 --> 00:45:28.530
Because it's likely that
they'll just opt out

00:45:28.530 --> 00:45:30.190
of that particular
type of notification

00:45:30.190 --> 00:45:31.870
rather than all of
your notifications.

00:45:31.870 --> 00:45:37.555
So you can minimize and mitigate
against negative impact.

00:45:37.555 --> 00:45:38.500
Yeah, that's it.

00:45:38.500 --> 00:45:42.300
That's my short lessons
learned on building an activity

00:45:42.300 --> 00:45:44.090
notification system.

00:45:44.090 --> 00:45:45.280
And thanks very much.

00:45:45.280 --> 00:45:47.080
